Around the time Apollo turned 12 he started suffering from arthritis and irritable bowel disease. We had to completely overhaul his diet and ensure he was getting all the nutrients he needed as a senior dog.

Over the last two years I’ve learned a lot about dog nutrition (especially for pugs) and have tweaked and perfected a homemade dog food recipe that I wanted to share.

Generally we use this homemade dog food as a topper to their usual kibble or raw meals so it lasts a long time — usually over two weeks for two hungry pugs!

Nutrient-Dense Dog Food Recipe:

4 boneless chicken breasts (or thighs if you’re willing to take the extra step to debone)
1 - 2 Tablespoons Coconut Oil
1 - 2 Tsp Turmeric
1 Cup Veggies (we use frozen peas or broccoli most often)
1 Cup Rice (cooked in bone broth for added nutrients and minerals)
1 Tablespoon Crushed Egg Shells

Make rice with your preferred method. Let cool while you prep the other ingredients.

Sauté chicken breasts in a small amount of coconut oil until cooked. Remove and set aside. Melt remaining coconut oil in the same pan. Add turmeric and sauté for one minute.

Add veggies and chicken to a food processor. Once chopped, add to a bowl and combine with the rice, turmeric oil, and the egg shells.

Serve!

This recipe freezes well so I often make a big batch like this and freeze it in smaller containers for use over two weeks.

The turmeric and coconut oil are potent inflammation reducers, especially for older pets. The egg shells add extra calcium and help reduce kitchen waste too! I’ve really seen an improvement in Apollo’s joint mobility since I’ve added these extras to his usual “chicken and rice” meal.

Today I’m sharing a very special recipe… one we make at least once a week. These instant pot egg bites are very easy, nutritious and way healthier than the Starbucks version (not to mention cheaper!).

How To Make Instant Pot Egg Bites:

7 Eggs
1 oz Cream Cheese
1 oz Cottage Cheese
Two Big Handfuls of Spinach
Protein and/or Veggies of Choice

Mix the eggs, cream cheese, cottage cheese and spinach together with an immersion blender (a regular blender works too!). Add cut-up protein and veggies. 

Prep instant pot by adding a cup of water to pot. Spray egg molds with cooking spray (I use coconut to avoid trans fats). Pour mixture into molds about 2/3 full. Add lids, stack into the instant pot and set for 10 minutes pressure cook. 

Once done cooking leave in the instant pot for five minutes then release pressure and serve! 

We make a big batch of these every couple of days and reheat them in the microwave for a quick healthy breakfast!

I know I haven’t done one of these since March — I did a “no buy” April for Earth Day and spent most of May and June hiding my 🤰🏼 bump. So time for a round up of everything I bought and loved this past spring!

What I bought & loved in Spring 2023:

- Zara Tunic Dress ($45 now on sale for $30). I bought this at the beginning of May and have worn it nonstop since. The fabric is light, airy and flattering. And there’s plenty of room for my growing bump all summer 💪🏻
- Birkenstock Big Buckle Sandals ($140). My last pregnancy all I wore were the Birkenstock waterproof Arizona sandals so this pregnancy I decided to upgrade myself to real leather. Love the sandstone color way with my pale skin and appreciate that the big buckle gives these sandals a more stylish look.
- Of An Origin Maternity Joggers (c/o $64). When this local brand reached out to me on Instagram I was immediately intrigued. It’s really frustrating how many pregnancy clothes are made from nonorganic fabrics and loved this brand’s ethos in providing capsule wardrobe pieces for pregnancy and postpartum. I’ve had these joggers for two weeks now and am LIVING in them. They have plenty of stretch left for the rest of my pregnancy and are insanely soft. I legit want this fabric for my sheets now 😂
- Serenity Wear Black Silk Blouse ($230). I’ve worn pieces for years — I bought my first silk dress from them in 2018. Their pieces are unbelievable quality and utterly beautiful. So when I saw this black silk blouse go on sale in May I took the plunge. Looks great buttoned, unbuttoned as a jacket or tied as a crop top. I bought an XL so I’d be able to wear it throughout my pregnancy too. These pieces are an investment so if you ever see them on sale don’t hesitate. Quality that truly lasts!
- H&M Print Dress ($28). My last pregnancy was still during pandemic shut downs so I didn’t have very many pieces for going out this time around. When @milada.vardiani wore this same dress to brunch one day I immediately knew I needed it for summer too. Who doesn’t need an airy black and white goes-everywhere dress? But I especially recommend it for anyone pregnant looking for something chic and easy to wear all summer!

What I Bought & Loved in Spring 2023 (Part Two):

- Zara Tulle Cover-Up ($55, on sale for $30). I grabbed this beautiful, drapey tulle cover-up during the Zara summer sale. I love that it’s an easy, bump-friendly way to upgrade any outfit for evenings. I can’t wait to wear this out for a dinner date with the girls! And hopefully I’ll be able to use this for a fun maternity shoot this fall too 🤍
- Amazon Cutout Dress ($27). A non maternity maxi that’s perfect for summer. I love the shoulder pads, the side cutouts and the twisted front. And that the design means my bump can grow with it for a few more months.
- Amazon Cargo Pants ($33). @itsamandaroe sold me on these easy cargo pants and I have no regrets. They’re so cozy but pulled together and somehow seem to make my 2nd trimester bump just disappear!
- Happy B Boutique Tee ($20). My good friend @katiebengson makes these tees for her Etsy shop and any RHOBH fans will recognize my “Carcass Out” tee 🍋. She customizes the most amazing @bravotv and holiday shirts — I love all my pieces from her shop and will especially be living in this tee all summer long!
- Agent Nateur Holi(radiance) ($55). An amazing beauty supplement. I’ve been using this @agentnateur supplement in my morning coffee for the last month and have absolutely noticed an improvement in my skin tone and texture. Can’t wait to see how this continues to improve my skin in the coming months!

- Cryofacial (a summer pregnancy MUST! The frigid treatment feels positively delicious and gave my skin such a plump, young appearance)

I cannot believe how smooth and glowy my skin is! The entire studio was a gorgeous space and my aesthetician @slkskin.x.sadie was so knowledgeable. She had so many ideas to help with my wacky hormonal pregnancy skin! @keelygoshia had a similar service two weeks ago so be sure to watch her reel too so you can see just how great these services are on different skin types 🫶🏻

Thank you so much for having me @nicole.facefoundrie.chicago @alexismichelleskin 🤍 And be sure to mention ‘MushroomStew’ for a discount on your services too

Everything about becoming a Mom is both beautiful and challenging. Often at the same time. And one of the biggest challenges I’ve faced in this early toddler stage is finding nutrient-dense snacks that aren’t super processed that Owen will actually eat. So for any Mamas struggling with this too, here’s a guide of what’s working for us now…

My Toddler’s Favorite Snacks (18+ Months)

1. Coconut Yogurt Bark. This has been trending a lot on TikTok and is a great, cooling summer snack. Feel free to use coconut or regular yogurt. I use @harmlessharvest vanilla yogurt. I just spread it onto a tray with parchment paper and dot it with yummy bites like freeze-dried or fresh fruit, chia seeds, honey or even chopped nuts. Freeze for an hour then break up to serve.

2. Collagen Fruit Smoothies. Another great summer snack, I take @perfectsupplements grassfed collagen, a milk of choice (we prefer raw milk), a banana, some strawberries or blueberries and some chia or flax seeds. Blend and serve for a sweet snack that’s still full of protein. Add coconut oil or a nut butter for added fat if desired.

3. Tart Cherry Gummies. I make these with molds at home to cut down on the sugar and ingredients. Just tart Cherry juice and grassfed gelatin. I make a big batch every few days and give these to Owen when he needs a quick snack full of amino acids and glycine.

4. Seaweed Nori Sheets. A great crunchy way to sneak in extra greens into your toddlers diet. I carry these in my diaper bag everywhere for a quick, compact snack.

5. Lesser Evil Lil Puffs. We alternate between these and the @myserenitykids puffs. Both are made from cassava flour so are gluten-free with some vegetables thrown into the mix. Expensive (considering how quickly Owen wolfs these down) but delicious and fun for him to eat.

6. Salmon Fish Roe (Ikura). This was one of Owen’s first foods (as recommended by @westonaprice) and still one of his favorites. It’s a quick, easy way for me to pack extra omegas into his day!

For me, one of the best things about Italian cuisine is the incredible range of flavors and ingredients. Dishes in Parma will taste so different from dishes in Rome or Sicily. Each region has such distinctive flavors and yet all rely on fresh elements to make simple flavors sing.

This summer @iaccchicago is highlighting Calabrian cuisine and, knowing nothing about the region, I was instantly intrigued. This Southern region has found truly explosive ways to pack flavor into humble dishes. Through the use of Calabrian chilis (their most famous ingredient!), ‘njuda sausage, fresh vegetables and plenty of seafood, this oft-overlooked region has some of the best Italian flavors I’ve yet encountered!

Last month @sweetsanty and I were invited into Ristorante Agostino’s kitchen to get a first-hand experience of Calabrian cuisine. We made Fileia ‘Njuda (pasta in a tomato ‘njuda sauce), Rapini with guinciale and beans, and Frittera di Pesce (beautiful, lightly fried seafood). Each dish was simple but packed with so much flavor! 

Have you ever tried Calabrian cuisine before?

These tart cherry gummies have become Owen’s favorite so I’m sharing the recipe in case you’re looking for an inflammation reducing, Vitamin-C-packed snack. Simple, easy and very nutritious!

How to Make Tart Cherry Gummies

1.5 Cups Tart Cherry Juice (I use @lakewoodorganic )
4 Tablespoons Grassfed Gelatin (I use @perfectsupplements )

Pour one cup cherry juice in a pan over medium-low heat. Add gelatin to remaining half-cup of juice and mix to “bloom”. Add bloomed gelatin to heated cherry juice and stir to dissolve.

Pour mixture into a shallow pan or pipe into gummy molds. Place in fridge for at least two hours. Cut into bite size pieces if not using a mold and ENJOY! I’ll share the molds I use in stories!

My Toddler’s Favorite Toys (18+ Months)

The toddler years really are so much fun. Draining but so fun. I love how much Owen goes off to explore the world now! So for any toddler parents out there, I wanted to share a few of his favorite toys from the past few months!

Wooden Threader. A great, Montessori toy that facilitates hand-eye coordination and motor skills. Also very portable!

Bubble Machine. An obvious favorite — toddlers cannot get enough of bubbles! I’m pretty sure bubble was Owen’s third word after ‘Dada’ and ‘Mama’. 

Light Switch Box. Owen has an affinity for switches and nobs so this box has been a great toy for him. And keeps him away from the stove nobs and power strips we have around the house 💪🏻

Ride Along Cars. Owen received this fire truck as a gift when he was born but only recently has been big enough to enjoy it. He loves pushing it around more than riding it. We also have a plastic version from @suburbanmomedition that he adores too. 

Indestructible Books. @marlissahamgeri told me about these in March after I complained about the money I was losing to books. Despite my best effort Owen went through a phase where he’d rip, chew and tear every book in sight. These have saved us so much money and are still the books he asks me to read him the most.

Play Arches. My MIL gifted these @gathre arches when he turned one and they’ve been a perennial favorite since. He’s now big enough to stack them and carry them around the house too. I suspect we’ll get a lot of use out of them in the coming years!

Poppers. The ultimate distraction. As you can see, ours is pretty worn down from love! Another great fidget toy to help with motor skills and keep him entertained during restaurant and coffee shop stops. I always have one packed in my diaper bag!

Wood Shape Peg Board. A gift from my cousin @jenjevyour this toy has become one of Owen’s favorites! It’s helped him learn more complex problem-solving skills as well as shapes and colors!

This year I finally convinced my husband to help me grow zucchini. And how they’ve thrived!! We have so much zucchini, it’s unbelievable given we only have three plants. This quick, easy, raw zucchini recipe has become our weekly staple — it pairs perfectly with everything. And it’s ready in 5 minutes!

What You’ll Need:
Zucchini
Parmigiano-Reggiano
Pine Nuts
Good Olive Oil (I use @frantoi_cutrera)
Salt & Pepper

Take a mandolin or vegetable peeler and shave thin slices of the zucchini. Shave parmigiano-reggiano on top. Lightly toast pine nuts in a pan on the stove (watch them closely as they burn fast) and toss on top. Drizzle with good olive oil (cheap olive oil will ruin the beauty of the raw zucchini flavor) and season with salt and pepper. Serve as an appetizer or side salad!

Now that it’s officially fall, I decided to switch up my usual tart cherry gummies for these addictive mulled apple cider ones! They’re packed with vitamin c, protein, glycine and plenty of spice. A great, healthy alternative to sugar- and preservative-filled store-bought gummies

Apple Cider Gummies

1.5 Cups Apple Cider
1 Tbsp Mulled Spices (Optional)
4 Tbsp Grassfed Gelatin (I prefer @perfectsupplements)

Pour 1 cup apple cider into a pot. Add mulling spices (if using) — I use a tea infuser to make the spices easy to remove but you can also strain them out. Warm on medium heat.

Mix remaining 0.5 cups of cider with 4 Tbsp gelatin. Stir well. Add to warm pot and stir until gelatin is dissolved. 

Using a pipette, fill molds with warm gummy mixture. If you don’t have molds, muffin tins or pie pans work well too. Chill in fridge until set, about two hours. Enjoy all Autumn long!

It’s been a hard and heavy 10 days. So in hopes of cheering myself up (and hopefully some of you), I’m sharing my most requested recipe 🫶🏻 Not only is this spicy, sweet snack an incredible mood-booster, it’s also beyond addicting and shockingly easy to do.

Spicy Candied Bacon

1 Package Bacon (I like @nimanranch)
Couple Tbsps of Brown Sugar
Spicy Salt (I like @jenniferfisherkitchen but you can make your own mixing sea salt, cayenne and chili powder)

Preheat oven to 375. Line a baking tray with tin foil or parchment paper. Layer a rack on top and spray liberally with nonstick spray (I prefer coconut oil).

Place bacon slices on rack, sprinkle with brown sugar and then press the sugar into the slices being sure to break up any large clumps. Sprinkle slices with spicy salt then cook for about 30 minutes. Remove and allow to cool (or “candy”) for 10 minutes. Candied bacon keeps well for a week in an airtight container and can be easily broken onto salads, ice cream or served with pancakes. Enjoy!

A Healing Postpartum Bath.

When I gave birth to Owen we hardly had time to enjoy him & heal. We closed on our first house a week later and my first two months postpartum were a blur of unpacking boxes and learning to be a parent. It was nonstop mayhem.

This time I was determined to slow down and enjoy my first weeks with Hugh. At the advice of @birthrootscommunitymidwifery we hired @errinbald as a postpartum doula. I looked forward to having help with the laundry, the dogs and cooking meals since Hubby couldn’t take a paternity leave. But what I didn’t quite understand when I hired Errin was I was actually hiring a guardian of nourishment. Or at least that’s what I’ve dubbed her.

If I could put to words what her support these last few weeks has felt like the best I’ve come up with is “swaddled in tenderness and care”. There’s an old Chinese saying “nourish the mother if you want to nourish the family” but I never really appreciated it until these last few weeks of nourishment I’ve received. As she’s helped me recharge I’ve had so much more love and attention to give the boys (both human and pug alike).

And one of my favorite rituals she’s done so far has been a meditative postpartum bath. She steeped herbs for 24 hours beforehand and brewed me a rose petal and cocoa drink to nourish my heart chakras. She guided me through a meditation, lulling Hugh into a deep nap that lasted hours. Afterwards I got the single best nap I’ve had in a month. It was truly magical and the sort of experience all new mothers deserve.

For any new mamas out there reading this, consider investing in your postpartum support care. It’s been the single best decision I’ve made since having Hugh. From the bottom of my heart, thank you Errin for everything you’ve done to nourish me back these last few weeks 🤍

Hubby is out of town this week so I wanted to share one of my favorite “stupid-easy” meals that I make when he’s gone while have two kids to look after and no time. Because keeping the kids alive and cooking a dinner solo is not a skill I’ve mastered yet 😛

How to Make Crock Pot Turkey Legs

This recipe is very simple!

2 Large Turkey Legs
Olive Oil
Spices of Choice (I use Garlic, Onion, Paprika and Oregano — all from @thespicehouse)

Place rinsed and pat-dried turkey legs into crockpot. Drizzle with olive oil then sprinkle with seasoning.

Set on high for 3-4 hours. Serve warm.

See? Easy! The perfect slow-cooked protein when I don’t feel like doing ANY prep 🤤

Officially sharing my postpartum January uniform 🤍💪🏻

Let’s be real & raw… Postpartum is hard. My body is so different than it was a year ago. None of my old clothing fits. I’m stuck raiding my husbands coat closet for winter gear (thank god oversized coats are IN 😂). It’s hard not to feel like my identity (at least as far as I express it visually) is in a small crisis. I want to feel like myself. And yet the person I see in the mirror is so different.

She’s a warrior. I feel that everytime I look at my sons and think “I made you”. But she’s also vulnerable and fresh. This body I’m in looks so different. And dressing this body now is so different from the body I had three years ago before children.

Be kind to the postpartum mamas. They’re accepting their new bodies. Appreciating their new (mama) lives. And yet still coming to terms with the fact that accepting and appreciating are a journey. And sometimes it involves a lot of mourning what was. I may never be the size I was pre-baby. And while I wouldn’t ever change that, I’m still coming to terms with it.

So here’s my January uniform. It’s comfy, cozy, relatively pulled together and honestly the outfit I feel most like myself in this month. And can we have a moment for this lounge set?
